.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-177-## 7. NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-178-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-179-### Reversibility
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:180:- **NFR-R01**: Every step P0→P4 names an explicit rollback; the P4 global default-on keeps `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` as the documented, load-bearing kill-switch.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:181:- **NFR-R02**: Because compiled routing is byte-identical to legacy for matched hubs, any step's rollback is behavior-neutral by construction, not merely by test.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-182-
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-183-### Determinism
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-184-- **NFR-D01**: The fallback is deterministic: identical (hub config, manifest, flag) inputs always yield the same served-authority; drift is a pure function of a hash mismatch, not timing.
--
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md-199-- All-legacy fleet under flag-on: a valid state (e.g. every hub mid-edit), must read as degraded, not failed.
